# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: birdie-tebbetts
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1936-detroit-tigers-season] The **1936 Detroit Tigers season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1936-detroit-tigers-season] The team finished second in the American League with a record of 83–71, 19½ games behind the New York Yankees.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1936-major-league-baseball-season] The **1936 major league baseball season** began on April 14, 1936.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1936-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 27, with the New York Giants and New York Yankees as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1936-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 33rd World Series on September 30 and ended with Game 6 on October 6.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1936-major-league-baseball-season] In the fourth iteration of this World Series matchup, the Yankees defeated the Giants, four games to two, capturing their fifth championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1932, and their first in a four-World Series run.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1936-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Detroit Tigers from the 1935 season.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1936-major-league-baseball-season] The fourth All-Star Game was held on July 7 at National League Park in Boston, Massachusetts, home of the Boston Bees.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1936-major-league-baseball-season] The National League had their first All-Star victory, winning 4–3.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1936-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Braves changed their nickname to "Bees" this season; they would revert to the Braves in 1941.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1936-major-league-baseball-season] The 1936 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1936-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 22 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1936-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since the 1904 season (except for 1919) and would be used until 1961 in the American League and 1962 in the National League.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1936-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day, April 14, featured all sixteen teams, the first since the 1934 season.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1936-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on September 27 and featured fourteen teams (the Chicago White Sox and St.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1936-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns finished their season the day before).
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1936-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season which didn't feature all sixteen teams since the 1929 season.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1936-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between September 30 and October 6.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1936-major-league-baseball-season] 10 tie games (6 in AL, 4 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1936-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on September 30 and ended on October 6 with the New York Yankees defeating the New York Giants in the 1936 World Series in six games.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1936-major-league-baseball-season] Over 81 home games, the Cleveland Indians played 80 games at League Park and 1 game at Cleveland Stadium, on Sunday, August 2, against the New York Yankees.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1936-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the 2nd of 12 seasons since 1932 that saw the Indians play at both venues.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1936-major-league-baseball-season] With the renaming of the Boston Braves to the Boston Bees, Braves Field is renamed National League Park, nicknamed by fans as *The Bee Hive*.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] The **1937 Detroit Tigers** finished in second place in the American League with a record of 89–65.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] The team finished 13 games behind the New York Yankees.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Their winning percentage of .578 ranks as the 15th best season in Detroit Tigers history.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] The strength of the 1937 Tigers was hitting.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers had scored 900 or more runs each season from 1934 to 1937.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] The 1937 total of 935 runs is the second highest in franchise history, trailing only the 1934 Tigers team that scored 958 runs.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] The 1937 Tigers led the major leagues with a .292 batting average—nine points higher than the Yankees.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] The 1937 Tigers also had power, belting twice as many home runs (150 to 74) as the 1934 team.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Second baseman Charlie Gehringer won both the American League batting title and the AL Most Valuable Player Award.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] First baseman Hank Greenberg led the major leagues with 183 RBIs—still the third highest single season total in major league history.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Rookie catcher Rudy York did not make it into the starting lineup until early August and promptly broke the AL record with 18 home runs in the month.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] York finished as the AL leader in at bats per home run (10.7) and with the third highest slugging percentage (.651) in the major leagues.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] While the team had the bats, it lacked the pitching to compete with the Yankees.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] In contrast to its league-best batting average, the Tigers pitching staff had an ERA of 4.87—ranking seventh among the eight American League teams.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Elden Auker (17–9; 3.88) was the only pitcher on the staff with an ERA below 4.00.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Former ace Schoolboy Rowe was suspended at the beginning of the year for poor conditioning, pitched only 31.1 innings for the year, and compiled a staggering 7.59 ERA.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] The team continued to have strong support from Detroit fans, finishing the 1937 season with a team record 1,072,276 fans attending the team's home games at Briggs Stadium.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] The only American League team to draw more fans up to that time was the 1930 Yankees' team that drew 1,169,230.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] The 1937 season began with **Mickey Cochrane** as the team's player/manager.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] However, Cochrane's playing career came to a sudden end on May 25, 1937.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] After hitting a home run in the third inning, Cochrane was hit in the head by a pitch from Yankees pitcher Bump Hadley when he next came to bat.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Hospitalized for seven days, the injury nearly killed him.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Ordered by doctors not to play baseball again (he was just 34 years old), Cochrane returned to the dugout but never played again.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Backup catcher Ray Hayworth had his arm broken by a pitched ball shortly after Cochrane's injury, and Birdie Tebbetts took over the catching duties for most of June and July.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] At the beginning of August, rookie **Rudy York** took over as the team's catcher and set the league on fire with his home run hitting.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] In August 1937, his first full month in the major leagues, York broke Babe Ruth's major league record for most home runs in a single month, hitting 18 home runs (and 44 RBIs).
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] For the year, York hit .307 with a .651 slugging percentage, 35 home runs, and 103 RBIs.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Defensively, York was a liability at catcher, leading the AL in passed balls in 1937 despite playing only two months.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] In 1940, the Tigers persuaded Hank Greenberg to move to left field, allowing York to take over at first base.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] York was among the American League leaders in home runs for 11 consecutive seasons from 1937 to 1947, and his .503 slugging percentage as a Tiger ranks #4 in franchise history.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] The Detroit infield remained intact for five years from 1933 through 1937: Hank Greenberg at first, Charlie Gehringer at second, Billy Rogell at shortstop, and Marv Owen at third.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] They were a solid group both at the bat and defensively.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] In 1937, Greenberg led the AL in putouts with 1477, and Gehringer, Rogell, and Owen all led the league in fielding percentage at their position.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Shortstop **Billy Rogell** led all AL shortstops in fielding percentage each year from 1935 to 1937, and in 1937 he hit .276 and scored 85 runs.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Rogell and Gehringer played over 1,000 games together as the Tigers' double play combination.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Rogell's fiery demeanor was a stark contrast to the calm, quiet demeanor of Gehringer.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] After retiring from baseball, Rogell served on the Detroit City Council from 1942 to 1980 .
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] He was chairman of the city planning committee that built Detroit Metropolitan Airport, and the road entering the airport from the north, Merriman Road, changes its name to William G.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] In the outfield, the Tigers had Gee Walker, Pete Fox, and Jo-Jo White.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Right fielder **Pete Fox** was a mainstay in the Detroit outfield for eight seasons (1933–1940).
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] He played on three AL pennant champion teams, and he was the Tigers' leading hitter in the 1935 World Series.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Though a native of Indiana, Detroit became his adopted home, and he died there in 1966.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] In 1937, Fox hit .331 and was among the league leaders with 149 singles (3rd), 208 hits (6th), 116 runs scored (8th), and 12 stolen bases (10th).
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Center fielder **Jo-Jo White** played in the Tigers' outfield from 1932 to 1938.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] He hit .313 in 1934, but his average fell off after that year.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] In 1937, Jo-Jo hit .246 and played only 94 games.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] White's real first name was Joyner, but he was called "Jo-Jo" because of the way he pronounced his native state of Georgia.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Rookie Chet Laabs also played 62 games in the outfield for the 1937 Tigers.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Labs hit .240 with a .434 slugging percentage.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] In 1938, Laabs struck out five times in one game against Bob Feller, helping Feller set the all-time record with 18 strikeouts in a nine-inning game.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Laabs later hit 27 home runs with 99 RBIs for the 1943 St.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Hall of Famer Goose Goslin also played in 39 games, but his batting average fell to .238 with 43 hits and 35 RBIs.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers released Goslin on October 3, 1937, and Goslin later recounted (in "*The Glory of Their Times*") that he received a call from his old boss, Clark Griffith, asking him if he'd be interested in ending his career back where it began in Washington.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Goslin jumped at the opportunity and batted .158 in 38 games for the Senators in the 1938 season.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] The Senators played in only three World Series in their history (1924, 1925, and 1933), and Goslin played for the Senators in every game of those Series.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] After three consecutive 20+ win seasons, **Tommy Bridges** dropped to a 15–12 season with a 4.07 ERA.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] He continued, however, to be among the league leaders with 138 strikeouts (5th in the AL).
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Bridges played in four World Series and six All-Star Games with the Tigers.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] One of the hardest throwers of the 1930s, Bridges was among the AL leaders in strikeouts 12 times and led the league in strikeouts in 1935 and 1936.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Rookie **Boots Poffenberger** was called up to the Tigers mid-season and went 10–5.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] His won-loss percentage of .667 in 1937 was seventh best in the AL.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Boots was only 21 years old when he debuted with the Tigers, and his career spun out of control within two years.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Stories about Poffenberger's late night drinking and poor training practices caused him to fall out of favor with the team.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] After a night of heavy drinking while on the road in 1937, Poffenberger called room service and said, "I'll have the breakfast of champions." When asked if he wanted cereal, Poffenberge replied, "Hell, no.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Pitcher **"Whistling Jake" Wade** also had his most productive season in 1937, posting career highs in wins (7), starts (25), complete games (7), strikeouts (69) and innings pitched (165-1/3).
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Wade pitched a one-hit shutout in the last game of the 1937 regular season, preventing Cleveland pitcher Johnny Allen from tying the AL record of 16 straight wins.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] However, Wade struggled with control and was among the AL leaders in 1937 with 107 walks allowed (7th) and five wild pitches (8th).
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Wade was nicknamed "Whistling Jake" not for his fastball but because of his tendency to whistle whenever he was nervous.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1939-detroit-tigers-season] The **1939 Detroit Tigers season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1939-detroit-tigers-season] The team finished fifth in the American League with a record of 81–73, 261⁄2 games behind the New York Yankees.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-cincinnati-reds-season] The **1940 Cincinnati Reds season** was the 58th season for the franchise.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati entered the season as the reigning National League champion, having been swept by the New York Yankees in the World Series the previous year.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-cincinnati-reds-season] They would defeat the Detroit Tigers four games to three to take the World Series title.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati won 100 games for the first time in franchise history.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-cincinnati-reds-season] The team finished first in the National League with a record of 100–53, winning the pennant by 12 games over the Brooklyn Dodgers, and the best record in MLB.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-cincinnati-reds-season] They went on to face the Detroit Tigers in the 1940 World Series, beating them in seven games.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-cincinnati-reds-season] This was their first championship since 1919.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-cincinnati-reds-season] In August, back up catcher Willard Hershberger, depressed over what he felt was culpability for losing both games of a doubleheader, took his life.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-cincinnati-reds-season] Coach Jimmie Wilson was added to the roster as the back up catcher.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-cleveland-indians-season] The **1940 Cleveland Indians season** was a season in American major league baseball.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-cleveland-indians-season] The team finished second in the American League with a record of 89–65, one game behind the Detroit Tigers.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-cleveland-indians-season] Had the Indians finished ahead of the Tigers, The Indians would have played their cross state National League rivals, the National League Champion Cincinnati Reds, in the World Series.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-cleveland-indians-season] The World Series would have been the only all Ohio World series.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-cleveland-indians-season] The season is infamous for ten Indian players confronting owner Alva Bradley and demanding the removal of manager Ossie Vitt, saying the man's behavior was harming the team.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] The **1940 Detroit Tigers season** was their 40th since they entered the American League in 1901.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] The team won the American League pennant with a record of 90–64, finishing just one game ahead of the Cleveland Indians and just two games ahead of the New York Yankees.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] It was the sixth American League pennant for the Tigers.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] The team went on to lose the 1940 World Series to the Cincinnati Reds 4 games to 3.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] The 1940 Tigers won the American League pennant with a record of 90–64.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] They narrowly beat the Cleveland Indians led by Bob Feller in a tight pennant race that went back-and-forth right down to the end of the season.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers outscored their opponents 888 to 717 for the season.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Catcher **Birdie Tebbetts** played for the Tigers from 1936 to 1947, missing the 1943–1945 seasons for military service.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] He was chosen four times for the AL All Star team.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] In 1940, Tebbetts hit .296 and led all AL catchers in assists (89), errors (17) and double plays (10).
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Catching duties were shared with **Billy Sullivan, Jr.**.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] He hit .309 with a .399 on-base percentage and .450 slugging percentage for the 1940 Tigers.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Sullivan played in 5 of 7 games of the 1940 World Series for the Tigers, scoring three runs with a .389 on-base percentage.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] His father, Billy Sullivan, was also a catcher for the Tigers in 1916.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] First baseman **Rudy York** started as a catcher in 1937.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] The experiment was successful, as York finished 2nd in the AL in RBIs (134), total bases (343), and extra base hits (85).
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] He also finished 8th in the AL MVP voting, 3rd in the major leagues in times on base (279) and doubles (46) and 4th in the AL in slugging percentage (.583).
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Shortstop **Dick Bartell** was known as one of the most ferocious competitors of his era.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] In 1940, he hit only .233 for the Tigers, but he had 76 walks boosting his on-base percentage by 100 points to .335.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] He scored 76 runs and drove in 53 runs for the 1940 season.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Bartell finished 12th in the AL MVP voting in 1940.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Third baseman **Pinky Higgins** was the team's starting third baseman from 1939 to 1944.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] In 1940, he hit .271, drove in 76 runs, hit 13 home runs, and walked 61 times, boosting his on-base percentage to .357.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Left fielder "Hammerin' Hank" Greenberg was the team's and the league's MVP.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] He was awarded the AL Most Valuable Player award for the second time in his career, the first person to win the MVP award at two different positions (1935 at first base, 1940 at left field).
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] In 1940, Greenberg led the major leagues in RBIs (150), extra base hits (99), slugging percentage (.670), OPS (1.103), total bases (384), doubles (50), and runs created (166).
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] He also led the AL in home runs (41) and at bats per home run (14.0).
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] He was 4th in AL in batting average (.340) and 2nd in the major leagues in on-base percentage (.433), runs scored (134), and times on base (289).
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Greenberg was drafted into the military in early 1941 (one of the first major league players to be drafted) and lost parts of five seasons (1941–1945) to military service.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Center fielder **Barney McCosky** also had a tremendous year.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] For the 1940 season, McCosky led the major leagues in hits (200) and triples (19).
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] He was also 3rd in the major leagues in runs scored (123), and 4th in the AL in times on base (268), 5th in the AL in batting (.340).
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] In the World Series, he hit .304 (7-for-23) with five runs.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] McCosky finished 16th in the 1940 AL MVP voting.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Since 1940, the only Tiger to exceed McCosky's 19 triples is Curtis Granderson in 2007.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Right fielder **Pete Fox** played 82 games in right field, hitting .289 with a .403 slugging percentage.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Hall of Famer Earl Averill was acquired by the Tigers in 1938 and was a backup outfielder for the 1940 team.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Closer **Al Benton** led the major leagues in saves (17) and was second in the major leagues in games finished (35).
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Rookie **Floyd Giebell** was one of the most interesting stories of the 1940 season.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Giebell made his major league debut in September 1940 as a 30-year-old rookie.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Giebel pitched a pair of complete game victories and gave up only two runs in 18 innings for an earned run average of 1.00.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] On September 27, 1940, the Tigers needed one more win to clinch the pennant.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] With Bob Feller scheduled to pitch for the Indians, Detroit manager Del Baker decided to start Giebell rather than "waste" his aces Bobo Newsom or Schoolboy Rowe.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] *Time* magazine described Giebell at the time as "a gawky stringbean" — Geiebell was 6 ft 2+1⁄2 in (189 cm) and 172 pounds (78 kg) —who "looked like a sacrificial lamb as he ambled out to the mound." But, as *Time* reported after the game, Giebell was "no lamb" that day.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Instead, "[w]ith cunning change of pace and the control of an oldtimer, the green-as-grass rookie shut out the Indians 2-to-0." Feller gave up only 3 hits for the day, but one of them was a 2-run wind-blown home run by Rudy York.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Giebell shut out the Indians for 9 innings in one of the great "David vs.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] The **1940 World Series** featured the Detroit Tigers and the Cincinnati Reds, with the Tigers losing in 7 games.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] In Game 1, the Tigers beat the Reds, 7–2.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] It was the 10th straight World Series loss for a National League team.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers scored five runs in the 2nd inning, and Bruce Campbell added a two-run home run.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Bobo Newsom held the Reds to eight hits.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Newsom's father, visiting from South Carolina, died in a Cincinnati hotel room the day after watching his son win Game 1.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] In Game 2, Bucky Walters gave the NL its first World Series game victory, 5–3, since Carl Hubbell beat the Yankees in 1937.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Jimmy Ripple hit a two-run home run in the 3rd inning, and Walters gave up only 3 hits.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] In Game 3, the Tigers won, 7–3, before a crowd of almost 53,000 at Briggs Stadium.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers had 9 hits and 19 total bases in the 7th and 8th innings off the Reds.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Paul Derringer‚ who had lost 4 World Series starts going back to 1931‚ finally got a win.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit starter Dizzy Trout did not make it out of the third inning.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] In Game 5, Bobo Newsom got the start for Detroit, just three days after his father's death.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Bobo said he was going to pitch the game for his dad.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] In front of 55,000 fans in Detroit, he shut out the Reds, as the Tigers won 8–0, and took a 3–2 lead in the Series.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] In Game 6, Bucky Walters got the win for the Reds with a 4–0 shutout.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] The concluding game was a loss for the Tigers, as Bobo Newsom was called on to start on only one day's rest.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit got an unearned run in the 3rd inning to take a 1–0 lead.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] Newsom pitched well, allowing only two runs in the 7th inning.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/1940-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers scored only once, and the Reds won, 2–1.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] Although he lacked speed and did not hit for power, Tebbetts was an exceptional defensive catcher and intelligent player who capably directed his pitchers.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] These traits served him well later in his career, as he became the manager for the Cincinnati Reds, Milwaukee Braves and the Cleveland Indians.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] His major league career encompassed 14 years as a catcher, 11 as a manager and 28 as a scout.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] Tebbetts was born in Burlington, Vermont, but his family moved to Nashua, New Hampshire a few months after he was born.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] Shortly thereafter, his father died, leaving his mother to raise the family.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] Some reports state that Tebbetts acquired his nickname as a boy after an aunt observed that his voice sounded like a bird chirping, while other reports state the nickname was acquired while attending Providence College.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] Tebbetts was a bat boy for the Nashua Millionaires as a child, also serving as a catcher for pitchers warming up.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] Tebbetts was a star athlete at Nashua High School where he attained All-State status as a football quarterback and as a baseball catcher.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] He signed a contract with the Detroit Tigers after they agreed to pay his college tuition.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] He attended Providence College where he became an All-American in baseball before graduating with a degree in philosophy in 1934.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] He also suffered an appendicitis in college, causing him to miss several months of baseball.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] The Tigers purchased future Hall of Fame catcher Mickey Cochrane from the Philadelphia Athletics in December 1933, leaving no place for Tebbetts on the team.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] He spent the next three seasons playing in the minor leagues before making his MLB debut with the Tigers on September 16, 1936 at the age of 23.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] In the 1937 season, Cochrane's playing career came to an end when he was hit by a pitch and suffered a fractured skull.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] Rudy York replaced Cochrane as the Tigers' catcher, but his defensive skills were so poor that by the 1939 season, new Tigers manager Del Baker gave Tebbetts a chance to play.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] Tebbetts ended the season with a .261 batting average and led American League (AL) catchers in assists and in baserunners caught stealing.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] In 1940, York was converted into a first baseman, leaving Tebbetts in sole possession of the catcher's position.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] He responded by posting a .296 batting average, as the Tigers defeated the Cleveland Indians and the New York Yankees in a tight pennant race to clinch the American League title.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] Tebbetts was held hitless in the 1940 World Series as the Tigers lost to the Cincinnati Reds in a seven-game series.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] He once again led AL catchers in assists and in baserunners caught stealing.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] In September, Tebbetts had been charged with assault and battery during a game in Cleveland when a basket of tomatoes was dropped on him by a Cleveland fan.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] As police held the fan, Tebbetts rushed up and struck him.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] Tebbetts developed a reputation for antagonizing opposing players, constantly heckling them in an effort to have them make mistakes and give his team an advantage.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] In his autobiography, Tebbetts said he and catcher Mike Tresh helped umpire Red Ormbsy call balls and strikes during a game when Ormsby suffered from a dizzy spell.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] Tebbetts tipped Ormsby off with hand signals following each pitch.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] In 1941, Tebbetts was hitting for a .296 average by mid-season and earned a place as a reserve player for the American League in the 1941 All-Star Game.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] He led American League catchers in assists for a third consecutive year.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] Tebbetts was named the starting catcher for the American League in the 1942 All-Star Game.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] Despite holding a 3-A draft classification because of his mother's dependency, Tebbetts applied for an Army Air Corps commission.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] He joined the military services in August 1942 and was assigned to recruiting duties in Waco, Texas during the Second World War.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] Tebbetts honed his managerial skills as a player-manager for the Waco Army Flying School's baseball team.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] He lost three years of his baseball career to his military service.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] After his discharge from the military, Tebbetts returned to play for the Tigers in 1946, posting a .243 batting average in 86 games.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] He was hitting for only a .094 average in May 1947 when he was traded to the Boston Red Sox for catcher Hal Wagner.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] After the trade, Tebbetts hit for a .299 average for the remainder of the season.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] There were reports in July 1947 that the Red Sox were considering Tebbetts as a successor to their manager, Joe Cronin.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] He was hitting for a .286 average at mid-season in 1948 and was named as a reserve catcher for the American League in the 1948 All-Star Game.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] The Red Sox finished the season in a first place tie with the Cleveland Indians before losing the pennant in a one-game playoff at Fenway Park.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] Tebbetts was elected to be the starting catcher for the American League in the 1949 All-Star Game.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] He hit for a .270 average in 1949 as the Red Sox engaged the New York Yankees in a tight battle for the pennant that was not decided until the final game of the season.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] The Red Sox had a one-game lead with two games left to play in the season, but lost the final two games of the season against their New York rivals to once again finish in second place.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] In 1950, the 37-year-old Tebbetts shared catching duties with Matt Batts as he posted a career-high .310 batting average in 84 games.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] The Red Sox were once again involved in a tight pennant race before faltering to finish in third place in the standings.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] At a public speaking engagement in October, Tebbetts defended Red Sox manager Steve O'Neill from criticism he received from some of the Red Sox players.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] In his speech, Tebbetts called the critics "a couple of juvenile delinquents and moronic malcontents." His comments created friction within the team and two months later, his contract was sold to the Cleveland Indians.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] He spent the final two seasons of his career as a backup catcher for perennial All-Star Jim Hegan.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] Tebbetts played his final major league game on September 14, 1952 at the age of 38 although in a news report in December 1952, Tebbetts admitted that his actual age was 43, saying that he subtracted five years off his age after he left college.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] In a fourteen-year major league career, Tebbetts played in 1,162 games, accumulating 1,000 hits in 3,704 at bats for a .270 career batting average along with 38 home runs, 469 runs batted in and an on-base percentage of .341.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] He ended his career with a .978 fielding percentage.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] A four-time All-Star, Tebbetts led American League catchers four times in range factor, three times in assists, twice in baserunners caught stealing, and once in putouts.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] Before the arrival of Hall of Fame catcher, Carlton Fisk, Tebbetts was voted the Red Sox' all-time best catcher in a 1969 fan poll , a remarkable feat, considering that he spent only four years with the Red Sox.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] In December 1952, the Indians General Manager, Hank Greenberg, named Tebbetts as the manager of the Indianapolis Indians.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] After Tebbetts guided Indianapolis to a fourth-place finish in 1953, he was hired by Gabe Paul to replace Rogers Hornsby as the manager of the Cincinnati Reds.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] After leading the Reds to fifth-place finishes in 1954 and 1955, Tebbetts led the team to a surprising third-place finish in 1956.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] The Reds were in first place at mid-season and stayed in the pennant race until the last day of the season, ending up with a 91–63 record, two games behind the Brooklyn Dodgers.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] For his efforts, the Baseball Writers' Association of America voted Tebbetts as the 1956 Manager of the Year.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] The Reds rewarded him with a three-year contract in December.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] In 1957, Tebbetts had the Reds in first place at mid-season, earning him a place on the cover of *Time* magazine in July of that year.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] The Reds faltered during the second half of the season and faded to finish in fourth place.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] Frank Robinson gave Tebbetts credit for his performance during the 1957 season saying, "He kept after me all year and that's what a young ball player needs." In 1958, the Reds fell into last place and Tebbetts announced his resignation on August 14.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] In October 1958, Tebbetts was hired as an executive vice president for the Milwaukee Braves.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] He served in the Braves front office from 1959 through September 1961, but found that he missed the excitement of being on the playing field.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] When the team fired Chuck Dressen in September 1961, Tebbetts returned to managing for the last month of the season.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] Ironically, his former team, the Cincinnati Reds, would win the National League pennant that year.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] Despite having talented players like Hank Aaron, Eddie Mathews, Joe Adcock, Warren Spahn, and Lew Burdette, Tebbetts could manage only a fifth-place finish in 1962.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] In October 1962, Tebbetts signed a three-year contract to manage the Cleveland Indians, saying that he felt he owed a long-standing debt to new Indians General Manager, Gabe Paul.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] After managing the Indians to a fifth-place finish in 1963, he suffered a heart attack during spring training in Tucson, Arizona on April 1, 1964.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] Just three months later, he returned to manage the team.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] After a fifth-place finish in 1965, Tebbetts led the Indians to fourteen victories in their first fifteen games of the 1966 season, but the team faltered and fell fifteen games out of first place before he resigned as manager in August.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] Tommy John remembered Tebbetts's advice for pitchers when they faced hitters they really struggled against: tell the hitter exactly what they were going to throw.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] This was meant to confuse the hitter, who would be unsure whether to believe the pitcher or not.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] In eleven seasons as a major league manager, Tebbetts compiled a 748–705 win–loss record.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] He returned to the minor leagues as a manager in 1967, managing the Marion Mets in the Appalachian League.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] From 1968 to 1997, Tebbetts scouted for the New York Mets, New York Yankees, Baltimore Orioles and the Florida Marlins.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] His baseball acuity earned him a reputation as one of the most respected scouts in professional baseball.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] Reggie Jackson credited Tebbetts' scouting reports for helping him hit three home runs in Game 6 of the 1977 World Series.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] He retired in 1997, having spent 60 years in baseball, including 53 years in the majors.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] Tebbetts moved to Anna Maria, Florida in the early 1960s.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] He was appointed to the Veterans Committee of the Baseball Hall of Fame in February 1979.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] He received the Judge Emil Fuchs Award in 1986 for his long and meritorious service in baseball.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] Tebbetts died on March 24, 1999, in Bradenton, Florida, at the age of 86.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] On May 28, 2009, Tebbetts was announced as a Local Legend of Nashua, New Hampshire, and commemorated with a plaque to be placed in Holman Stadium.
[src:birdie-tebbetts/birdie-tebbetts] He was inducted into the New Hampshire Interscholastic Athletic Association Hall of Fame in 2014.
